NII Holdings - Wikipedia






















 






NII Holdings

From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia


					Jump to:					navigation, 					search


NII Holdings, Inc.





Type

Public


Traded as
NASDAQ: NIHD


Industry
Wireless Services


Predecessor
Nextel[1]


Founded
1995[2]


Headquarters
Reston, Virginia, United States



Area served




Brazil






Key people

Steve Shindler (CEO)


Products
High speed networks, Two way messaging, Push to Talk


Revenue
USD 6.746 billion



Number of employees

16,089


Subsidiaries
Nextel Brazil 70% [3]


Website
www.nii.com


NII Holdings, Inc. (formerly Nextel International) is an American holding company that, through its subsidiary Nextel Telecomunicações Ltda., provides mobile communications services under the Nextel brand in Brazil.[4] NII operates iDEN, 3G UMTS/HSDPA, and 4G LTE networks in Brazil.
In 2012, for the third consecutive year, NII Holdings ranked in the Fortune 500 and Barron's 500 lists. NII also has been named one of the best places to work among multinationals in Latin America by the Great Place to Work® Institute.[5]
NII went through bankruptcy in 2014 and 2015.[6]




